I had never eaten, much less made, a tuna casserole in my life, but having recently gone vegetarian (except for fish), I needed recipes for my family's new lifestyle. This was a big hit with everyone, including my kids (ages 10 and 9)! Here's how I tweeked it to make it healthier and tastier: --I used low-sodium vegetable broth rather than chicken, and 2% milk rather than whole. --added 1 cup frozen peas with the mushrooms which was really good! --did not use soy, lemon, or sherry, rather (upon a reviewer's suggestion) I added a little ceyenne pepper and nutmeg to the roux, plus salt & pepper. --Used one can of tuna (drained), plus one 2 oz. pouch. Perfect. --added a little cheddar to the roux, per several reviewer's suggestions. --I used bagged shredded cheddar which worked just fine, and also whole wheat bread rather than white. Worked perfectly. I'll definitely be making this again! Rich, creamy, hearty, satisfying! Loved the crisp topping over the hot creamy filling!

Rating: 4
This was delicious. Here are my tweaks to make this gluten-free, lower in fat & salt, and to use fewer pans: * low-sodium tamari instead of soy sauce * 1/4 C Savory & James amontillado (no need to use my good sherry for cooking) * 1/4 C Bob's Red Mill GF all- purpose baking flour + 1 tsp Bob's Red Mill corn flour (to thicken the roux) * 2% milk instead of whole * 1/8 tsp. salt * 2 cans Pastene tonno--one 5 oz, one 3 oz (more would've been too fishy) * 3 slices Ener-G Light Tapioca Loaf * 6 oz Bionature fusilli * 4 0z Cabot 50% reduced fat sharp cheddar cheese * 1 tbsp olive oil insteaed of vegetable oil * ~ 1/2 bag of Cascadian Farm frozen peas (~8 oz) . Following others' suggestions, I cooked the pasta first, then used the same pot for the mushroom portion of the recipe. I placed the mushroom mixture in a bowl and used the same pot again to cook the rest of the recipe. This is a keeper.

