Rating: 4
It was 1975 and I was a 7th grade Home Economics student at Shenandoah Jr. High in Miami, Florida. Our teacher taught us how to make Tuna Casserole, a recipe I always loved and never forgot to make as it is the epitome of comfort kiddie food. Over the years I inevitably became an adult and snobbish about food and ingredients (use a can of cream of whatever... for a meal? Never!) so I hadn't considered this dish in over a dozen years. Then one night in May 2009 my pre-teen kids were sick and asking me to baby them and I told them I would make them my favorite dish as a kid. I pulled up this recipe and thought it had some nice touches with the soy sauce and the sherry. But then I got real and used the proverbial can of Campbell's Cream of Mushroom soup to substitute for the creamy sauce called for here. I am sure the sauce is fabulous, and tuna casserole is a winning dish especially for young families. But if you're feeling a little lazy, go for the canned cream soup and arrange the casserole as called for in this recipe. Skipping the sauce steps will save you 40 minutes and your family will still be satisfied, heartwarmed and feeling loved.

